   <abstract>Since the advent of New Public Management paradigms, scholars and practitioners have long been interested in how governance and political institutions efficiently and effectively manage public financial resources. However, recent movements have stressed the importance in understanding how public finance can aid in the execution and achievement in more "normative" policy priorities which go beyond standard economic theories of efficiency. This dissertation seeks to expand upon these nascent literatures by exploring the relationship between public policy and financial resource management in three different policy environments and normative outcomes. Through three studies which range in their theoretical application and methodological design, these essays contribute to numerous literatures on effective governance of public financial resources by (i) exploring different types of government levels' responses to financial resources within various political systems, (ii) analyzing various policy outcomes financial resources are tied to which vary in ambiguity and complexity, (iii) documenting the importance in viewing financial resource administration as both a management and policy purpose, (iv) identifying the importance in policy design of financial resource systems, and (v) exploring solutions to the oft-dilemma of constrained public institutions in working with constrained financial resources.</abstract>
